[Dimension Objective]  
Make "expression techniques/presentation strategies (including rhetorical devices)" the central scoring thread: identify the technique → specify textual evidence (feature + location) → explain its concrete effect on information presentation, structural coherence, rhetorical force/tone, or cognitive processing (specify target + causal chain).

[Item Design Guidelines]  
1) Assessable targets (focus on “expression and presentation effects”; do not evaluate validity or soundness):  
- Information presentation/expository strategies: definition, classification, exemplification, numerical listing, comparison, citation with explanation, visual/graphic or discontinuous presentation, etc.;  
- Structural and organizational strategies: general-to-specific/specific-to-general, parallel/progressive arrangement, transitional linkage, question-led introduction, contrast setup, paragraph progression design, etc.;  
- Linguistic strategies: qualifiers/degree adverbs, terminology definition and clarification, anaphora resolution, scope conditions, logical connectives, etc.;  
- Rhetorical devices (treated as expressive strategies): metaphor, personification, parallelism, antithesis, rhetorical/interrogative questions, repetition, quotation, hyperbole, etc. (only require explanation of their expressive or interpretive effects).  

Boundary note: If the stem asks examinees to judge whether an argument is valid, whether evidence is sufficient/rigorous, whether reasoning overreaches, or where logical flaws lie, this dimension should not serve as the primary scoring criterion; such items fall under CS15 or other reasoning-evaluation dimensions.

2) Question stems must explicitly reference specific sentences, paragraphs, or structural positions—avoid testing mere terminology recall:  
- Preferred phrasings: “What technique/strategy is used?” “What is the effect/function of this expression?” “How does this technique help readers understand/grasp the viewpoint?”

3) Effect descriptions must target verifiable aspects and articulate a clear causal chain (ban vague, formulaic responses):  
- Informational effect: greater accuracy, concreteness, or clarity of boundaries (e.g., qualifiers, definitions, data reducing ambiguity);  
- Coherence effect: clearer hierarchy or more explicit reading pathway (e.g., classification, parallelism, or progressive structuring of information);  
- Cognitive processing effect: highlighting key points, lowering comprehension load, aiding concept/relation construction (e.g., through explanation, anaphora resolution, or guiding questions);  
- Rhetorical force/tone and expressive intensity: emphasis, heightened engagement, or prompting reader attention/reflection (e.g., via parallelism, rhetorical questions, etc.).  

Note: Phrases like “enhances expressive power/persuasiveness” are acceptable only if linked to specific textual features and presentation mechanisms; do not assess evidential sufficiency or logical rigor.

4) Distractor design (for objective items/wrong options):  
- Misattribution: labeling a structural strategy as a rhetorical device, or a rhetorical device as an argumentative move;  
- Terminology without evidence: naming a technique without citing feature or location;  
- Effect-feature mismatch: attributing effects unrelated to the textual feature (e.g., claiming “emphasis/prominence” equates to “logical rigor/sufficiency,” which pertains to validity evaluation).

[Acceptance Criteria]  
- A full-credit response must include all three components:  
  (a) Correct identification of the technique/strategy (or an acceptable synonymous description);  
  (b) Textual evidence: explicit specification of “feature + location” (e.g., data, contrastive sentence, parallel structure, rhetorical question, transitional sentence, qualifier, etc.);  
  (c) Effect explanation: clearly state the target domain (information, coherence, cognitive processing, or rhetorical force/tone) and articulate a valid causal chain.  
- Errors or low-scoring responses can be attributed to: misidentification of technique, missing evidence, or an invalid causal link in the effect explanation.
